"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from Healthcare Financial Management Association (HFMA) (PEX 0017)&#xa0;\nThe Healthcare Financial Management Association (HFMA) is the representative body for finance staff in healthcare. For the past 60 years, it has provided independent and objective advice to its members and the wider healthcare community. We are a charitable organisation that promotes best practice and innovation in financial management and governance across the UK health economy through our local and national networks. We also analyse and respond to national policy and aim to exert influence in shaping the wider healthcare agenda. We have a particular interest in promoting the highest professional standards in financial management and governance and are keen to work with other organisations to promote approaches that really are ‘fit for purpose’ and effective.\nSummaryThis submission is based on the views of the HFMA and its members, drawing on the expertise and experiences of some of our most senior members.\nThe key points of our submission are:\n&#xa0;Detailed response Q1 The plans being made by NHS bodies to enable them to meet the Nicholson Challenge, and whether the NHS is succeeding in making efficiency gains rather than cutsQ2 The effectiveness of the mechanisms by which resources are distributed geographically in the NHS Q3 The prospects for the long-term viability of NHS Trusts and NHS Foundation Trusts (FTs)Q4 Reports of particular financial pressures in the system, such as funding general practice, and for accident and emergency servicesCost pressures\nIncome pressures\nDemand pressures\nQ5 The impact on the provision of adult social care of the 2010 spending review settlement and the ability of local authorities to make the necessary efficiency savingsQ6 The impact on NHS plans of decisions currently being made by local authorities and the use of the additional funding for social care being made available through the NHS budgetQ7 Progress on making efficiencies through the integration of health and social care services. Other views\n&#xa0;\nNovember 2013\n \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \nThe NHS belongs to the people: A call to action\n, NHS England, 2013\n \n2012/13 update on indicators of financial sustainability in the NHS\n, National Audit Office, 2013\n \nSummer Report for the period 1 April to 31 July 2013\n, NHS Trust Development Authority, 2013\n \nAnnual Plan Review 2013/14\n, Monitor, 2013\n \nThe arrangements have changed and as from 1 April 2013 FTs \nare issued with licences rather than terms of authorisation.\n \nReport of the Mid Staffordshire NHS Foundation Trust Public Inquiry\n, 2013\n \nEmergency admissions to hospital: managing the demand\n, National Audit Office, 2013\n \nBudget Survey 2013 Summary\n, ADASS, 2013\n \nA Promise to Learn – A Commitment to Act: Improving the Safety of Patients in England,\n National Advisory Group on the Safety of Patients in England, 2013\n \nReport of the Mid Staffordshire NHS Foundation Trust Public Inquiry\n, 2013\n"